<DOC><DOCNO> AP890213-0003 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-02-13-89 0001EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-Italy-Drought     02-13 0201</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Italy-Drought,0206</SECOND><HEAD>Italians Pray for Rain In Drought-Stricken Areas</HEAD><DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Thousands of people prayed for rain in northernItalian churches and some parched communities planned religiousprocessions, hoping to bring an end to one of the worst droughts inyears.   At 1,300 Roman Catholic churches in the diocese of Milan onSunday, priests invoked ``the rain that restores the earth andair,'' according to the diocese.   Churchgoers in Bergamo and Genoa have also been praying for rainas sunny, dry weather threatens crops and left ski slopes bare.   Several parishes in small towns south of Milan were planningprocessions along the Adda river if rain did not arrive in the nextfew days, the Italian news agency ANSA reported Sunday.   Italy has received only half the precipitation it usually gets inthe September-January period. The Milan area has had one rain showersince November 24, while Genoa has been dry for four months.   The lack of rain has prompted limits on private water use andcontributed to brush fires that have scorched thousands of acres innorthern Italy.   The dry weather is the result of a high-pressure system that hasremained over the Mediterranean for months, meteorologists say.</TEXT></DOC>